Polymorphism is one of the core concepts in object-oriented programming (OOP) and is implemented in C++. It is the ability of an object to take on many forms, depending on the context in which it is used.

In C++, polymorphism can be achieved through function overriding and function overloading.

**Function Overriding:**

Function overriding is a concept of function polymorphism where a derived class provides a different implementation of a function that is already defined in its base class. Both the base and derived classes have their own version of the function, but with different definitions.

```cpp
class Animal {
    public:
        void display() {
            cout << "This is an Animal";
        }
};

class Dog: public Animal {
    public:
        void display() {
            cout << "This is a Dog";
        }
};

int main() {
    Animal my_animal;
    Dog my_dog;
    my_animal.display();    // prints "This is an Animal"
    my_dog.display();       // prints "This is a Dog"
    return 0;
}
```

